			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-weight: bold">DISCLAIMER</span> <span style="font-style: italic">Magicians are not melee, this is a basic explanation of how Rampage works to the best of our knowledge.  Please be aware this information may not be 100% correct.</span>
<br />

<br />
Now, I think it's best to specify which era of "Rampage" we're discussing since Velious rampage works differently than Luclin and PoP rampage. While it may seem like a minor point, it is crucial in answering the question. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Velious-era Rampage</span>: 
<br />

<br />
To the best of our knowledge this is based on the amount of aggro a PC has through direct attacks and usually goes to the 2nd person on the "Aggro List". There is a range associated with this, but is greater than 200ft or so. Death will wipe you from the rampage list. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Example</span>: Warrior_01 engages NPC. Various melee attack the NPC. Wizard_01 chain nukes 5 GSS. Wizard_01 now has 2nd most aggro behind Warrior_01. NPC will rampage Wizard_01. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Luclin & PoP-era Rampage</span>: 
<br />
To the best of our knowledge this is based on the order of engagement regardless if it is a direct or indirect aggro on the NPC. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Example</span>: Warrior_01 engages NPC, Cleric_01 immediately heals Warrior_01 before another person has a chance to attack. In this case, Cleric_01 will immediately receive rampage attacks even though he/she did not physically harm the NPC. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic"><span style="text-decoration: underline">Sample Rampage List</span></span>
<br />

<br />
Since Luclin rampage is based on order of engagement, it is possible to "set up" the rampage list with your desired order by having Warriors and Knights shoot arrows or cast non-damage dealing spells on the target. Usually, you can prepare the rampage list to look something like this: 
<br />

<br />
1) Warrior_01 
<br />
2) Warrior_02 
<br />
3) Warrior_03 
<br />
4) SK_01 
<br />
5) Paladin_01 
<br />
6) Paladin_02 
<br />
7) Paladin_03 
<br />
8) SK_02 
<br />
9) SK_03 
<br />
10) SK_04 
<br />

<br />
The reason that I list 10 persons on the rampage list because it is believed that the rampage list is only 10 deep (in Luclin). 
<br />

<br />
The range on Luclin & PoP rampage appears to be between 100ft and 150ft. The first example that comes to mind is Arch Lich in Ssra Temple. The room is approximately 100ft wide and 200ft long. Arch Lich is positioned in such a way that the maximum distance possible from him is roughly 150ft maximum. From my experience, if you retreat to the back corners of the room, you can avoid his rampage. Death has no effect on your position on the rampage list. If you are rezzed and are in range, you will still be on the rampage list.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Conclusion</span>:
<br />

<br />
Since Velious rampage is aggro based and since CoH has the ability to wipe aggro, the conclusion that can be drawn is that: 
<br />

<br />
CoH can* remove you from the rampage list when encountering Velious era NPCs. 
<br />

<br />
Since Luclin rampage is order of engagement based and not aggro dependent, the conclusion that can be drawn is that: 
<br />

<br />
CoH will not remove you from the rampage list when encountering Post-Luclin era NPCs. 
<br />

<br />
*Disclaimer: It can remove you from the rampage list, provided that normal CoH rules are followed so that you are summoned the pre-requisite distance to clear aggro.
<br />

<br />
